ce:section.ce:para:
In this work, we demonstrate a CDs/HgL1 composite to improve the photocatalytic properties of HgL1 and investigate the roles of CDs in photocatalysis. The synthesized CDs/HgL1 produces H2O2 at a rate of 800 µmol h−1 g−1, which is 6.4 times that of pristine HgL1 (125 µmol h−1 g−1). Transient photovoltage (TPV) tests indicate that CDs/HgL1 has a higher surface effective electron number (n

                        e
                     ), which is one of the reasons for its improved performance. In-situ TPV tests confirm another role of CDs for boosting the activity of oxygen reduction reaction (ORR). Furthermore, in this system, CDs alter the catalyst surface from hydrophobic to hydrophilic, thus facilitating the reactions that follow. In a word, CDs participate in the entire photocatalytic reaction and promote the photocatalytic H2O2 production of pristine HgL1 by accelerating the electron-hole separation and migration, improving the redox activity and changing the surface from hydrophobic to hydrophilic. This work comprehensively analyzed the function of CDs in metallated graphyne based catalyst for photoinduced H2O2 production, gaining a better understanding of the roles of CDs.
